text:
green is my favourite colour i must say. i walked into this market shop and decided to indulge into a bit of shopping in a foreign land. turkey, in belek to be precise. a town with less women on the streets leaving boisterous men selling different types of merchandise. even the ladies up and about are mostly tourists just like me. so inside the shop i spotted a jungle green dress and i got smitten. i picked it, tried it and it was perfect. but the dress has it's own story. a tale that happens everyday everywhere in the world. a sad narrative. one so sad that i threw away the dress to avoid memories but at the same time posted it publicly to raise awareness. 
to be continued..

a kind of love story. of self love and preservation. and if we're here for love then we gotta look at all the ways it is expressed. it's been 25 years since 24 year old ecuadorian immigrant lorena bobbit chopped her rapist husband's dick right off.

i was 13, i remember the jokes and i'm sure i laughed. a dismembered dick? gross! weird! but i'd also already had so many strangers flash their shriveled and weird shaped parts at me, grab at me, that i felt some quiet satisfaction in knowing she'd done something about it.

there's a great story about her in @nymag with 4 brilliant writers penning their own sort of love letters to her. letters of understanding and empathy and solidarity. because her struggle is ours too. oh, and a documentary is coming out on friday.

text:
day 14 of sexual abuse in the black community:

tyler perry "in addition to the brutal physical abuse, tyler says he also suffered severe sexual abuse at the hands of four different adults.

tyler says he was 5 or 6 years old the first time he was molested. while building a birdhouse with an adult male neighbor, the man put his hands in tyler's pants, he says. "i'm thinking, 'what is this?'" tyler says. "and i felt my body betraying me, because i felt an erection at that age." tyler says he later endured sexual molestation at the hands of a male nurse and a man he knew from church. "[the man from church] used god and the bible against me to justify a lot of the things that were going on. it was so horrible," tyler says. "and that was my first sexual experience, with this man performing oral sex on me as a boy." read more here: https://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/tyler-perry-speaks-out-about-being-molested-and-the-aftermath

text:
during the 36-year-long guatemalan civil war, #indigenous women were systematically raped and enslaved by the military in a small outpost near the #sepurzarco community. what happened to them then was not unique, but what followed, changed history. from 2011, fifteen women survivors fought for justice at the highest court of guatemala. finally, in 2016, two former military officers were convicted of sexual violence, and sexual and domestic slavery. they were sentenced to 120 and 240 years of imprisonment, which included an additional thirty years in prison for both defendants for crimes against humanity, in recognition of the importance of punishing gender-based violence. this was the first time that wartime sexual violence was tried in the country, as well as the first time a national court ruled in a domestic and sexual slavery case.
now this process is under threat as the guatemalan congress is planning to grant blanket #amnesty to all wartime crimes against humanity. as a response, thirty-six maya-achÃ­ women survivors are challenging the proposed law in the constitutional court of guatemala. they ask the court to stop the bill because â€œit represents an attempt to manipulate the law to evade justice and to achieve impunityâ€. pictured: one reparation measure for the sepur zarco community that has had some traction is the free mobile health clinic, which serves 70 â€“ 80 people every day. â€œwe had to walk long to get to a clinic, but now itâ€™s closer. each community takes turn to take care of the clinic. many women from my community have received medicines, but there are sicknesses that cannot be treated hereâ€¦we dream of a hospital that can treat all our illnesses,â€ explained rosario xo, one of the survivors.

go to our story to read more about sepur zarco women!

photo: un women/ryan brown

today in black sistory we honor the silence 
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams swallowed 
while we were raped 
the screams tucked into the darkest places 
of our souls 
so as not to wake the children 
and see more horror in their eyes 
so as not to wake the men 
and see the pain of not being able to protect us 
the emasculation of being powerless 
when master rapes your wife 
we the sobs hushed 
we the refrains muffled 
we the words that didnâ€™t part from our teeth 
because 
we did best to know our place 
we did best not to be uppity 
or think that we may deserve dignity 
we that learned a down cast eye 
kept us alive 
we the tears flowing like waterfalls 
perpetually inside 
while our sons swung 
high 
and died 
our feet bleed beneath our skin 
our backs shredded within 
our lips closed and tight 
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite 
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children 
we learned too well 
we the tired 
we the weary
we the screams
we the sirens
we are silent no more 
you will hear us 
our feet marching 
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs 
like wind in our sails 
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long 
we will open our mouths 
and you will never hear the same again 
our screams will echo in your souls forever 
our #metoo began before hollywood 
before trump grabbed pussies 
stand with your alabaster tears 
for as long as you can 
but move when you hear my army 
move when you hear my battle cry 
move when you feel the presence of my lineage 
silent no more --leslÃ© honorÃ©

text:
virginia lt. gov. fairfaxâ€™s accuser speaks on stanford #metoo panel
#
a college professor avoided talking directly about her accusation that virginia's lieutenant governor sexually assaulted her, but she talked in detail about her research and thoughts on the growing number of women reporting abuse."one thing that i notice with sexual violence is that there are many people who would like to glance away from this," vanessa tyson told a stanford university symposium. "it's one of the ugliest parts of humanity. trust me."tyson, appearing tuesday night as one of two panelists at the event called "betrayal and courage in the age of #metoo", was making her first public appearance since she accused virginia lt. gov. justin fairfax of assaulting her in 2004. tyson is a political science professor at southern california's scripps college who is spending a year at stanford as a research fellow.fairfax said he recalled the encounter, which he said was consensual, and denied assaulting or coercing tyson."perhaps we have to reshape how we understand consent and how we teach it to society as a whole," tyson said during her talk, which also included her experience with students who were sexually assaulted confiding in her, and the difficulty victims have when institutions don't appear to take their claims seriously."speakingâ€¦

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: @mandymooremm i want you to know that you are so brave for speaking up about the abuse you went through. i hear you. i see you. and i stand with you. as someone who has gone through sexual harassment/assault, shaming and bullying (which i would call this verbal abuse). this breaks my heart. i am dedicated to making sure women do not have to through this alone. a forever goal of mine, is to help women who have gone through trauma. i want to reach out to women and help them as much as i possibly can. if i can do thatâ€”â€”inspire women, and help make a difference through my writing or blog posts then that will make me so so happy! i hope that no woman has to go through this alone. especially the other handful of women (@_fake_nudes_ , @tropicalijaye, @littlestmonkey ) who have come forward to share their stories for the @nytimes. so, my wish is for all women of trauma to join me and come together, to support one another, and be there for each other. because, you are not alone. ğŸ’•ğŸŒˆ also, if you have experienced any abuse, sexual assault, harassment, etc. please feel free to contact me at brittanyanndobbins@gmail.com, or dm me on insta. i will do my very best to help you through your trauma and give you some friendly advice! although i am not a therapist, i am here for you and i will listen to you. ğŸ’• so pls chat with me! :) @nytimes #ryanadams #mandymoore #thisisus #sexualharassment #metoomovement #metoo #timesup #feminism #womensupportingwomen #femaleempowerment #musicindustry #beauty #activism #advocacy #writer #sisterhoodforever #inspire #motivation #womeninpower #advice #trauma #musicindustry

text:
@contemporaryathon photo challenge day three: favourite nonfiction contemporary ğŸ’› every essay in this anthology is so important and timely.
.
.
.
"there's this impossible paradox when you are victimized byÂ sexual assault. you want to - you have to - convince yourself that it wasn't that bad in order to have any hope of healing. if it really is as bad as you feel like it is, how will you ever get out from under it? how will you ever get better? on the other hand, you need to convince others it was bad enough to get the help and support you need to do that healing. to get out from under it. to get an appointment at the clinic. to get friends to come over with styrofoam food containers when you can't feed yourself. you tell yourself how bad it is and then you numb yourself to how bad it is. you repeat as needed for so many years. does saying no 16 times make me worthy of pity? does it make me worthy of help?" - excerpt from "to get out from under it" by stacey may fowles
.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
as my grandma connie used to say: "what's love got to do with it?" // don't spend any more time loving someone who doesn't deserve it--even if....
.
.
you aren't a bad person for walking away. you aren't responsible to heal their trauma, you weren't  put on the earth for them or to be this person's punching bag or to satisfy anyone's inner demons.
.
.
even if you love them, even if they're struggling with their behavior upon reflection, even if they're trying to stop hurting you, or can't help but hurt you because 'when he was a kid;' even if he upholds himself as "minnesota nice"
.
.
you're not abandoning a victim by identifying ways in which they've abused you -- and removing yourself. maybe they'll find a therapist to help them heal someday ğŸ‘ or maybe not. it's not your problem! but they've probably somehow made you feel as though it is.
.
.
it's never wrong to protect yourself. it's easy to be blindsighted by compassion, understanding for another person's plight. to feel, like i did, that being an advocate means accepting abusive people into your home and heart and bed. to feel, like i did, that rage and obsession and control and uncontrollable sexual urges are signs of unbridled love. to feel, like i did, that one act of forgiveness was a contract that i must always forgive him.
.
protect yourself from being sucked into someone elses cycle of abuse. protect yourself against cyclical behaviors that result from previous traumas. being abused doesn't inherently mean a person will inflict trauma upon another; it's a special kind of fucked up to pass along sexual abuse from their body to your body.
.
soooo, bottom line, if you think your partner's past is hurting you....then....leave (easier said than done tho right?). then find yourself a good therapist so you don't sabatoge ur future.
.
.
here's to emdr, which helped me untangle myself from a person i thought i left years ago, and here's to dr young for helping me reframe it all so i could heal; and here's to loving myself and accepting my story a little more every day.
.
here and ğŸ’¯ not judging if anyone wants to talk about anything.
.
.
#survivornotvictim #emdr #cptsdrecovery #valentinesday2019 #metoo

first axe that comes to mind is the stanley 4 square, sweetheart edition. 
the sw for stanley works, and the heart for william hart, president of the company. 
stanley quit using the sw logo, then brought it back.  i'm not sure of the current status.  i haven't followed it much over the years but it is an interesting touch in the axe world.  i believe stanley bought one of the south american collins plant sites when mann edge took over.

text:
hark! over the horizon. a mighty fiend! it skulks over as it feels hiraeth for its long lost village. such ephemeral nonsense cannot escape me. this ruse has much to be worked upon. i grin with my slightly crooked teeth, and approach the beast. again, i see past its cromulent tears and slay it. as i look over yonder to the blazing sun, the temporarily defeated monstrosity takes a snapshot of my malicious countenance. it flees into the baobab tree, pleading for permanent solitude. and so, i move on.

#blessed #pugs #publicinfluencer #metoo #journeycontinues #puglover #dogs #momspaghetti

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
i donâ€™t share this often, but my first binge that i can clearly remember happened in elementary school. i sat at the island at my dadâ€™s new house and ate the cereal my mom never allowed at home: lucky charms.
.
the weekends i spent at my dadâ€™s house were the loneliest moments of my life - i canâ€™t even express the deep loneliness to you. it was so traumatic to me that i swear i had ptsd until recently, where i feel like iâ€™ve finally dealt with 90% of it. .
but the junk food made me happy for a second. i swear this is how the eating disorder stuff all started. swinging from â€œhealthyâ€ foods loaded with diet terms at momâ€™s to fast food and super-processed junk food at my dadâ€™s + trying to navigate the world of being a girl in a really effed up family situation. .
even just thinking about being that little girl again makes me want to cry as i write this. when i revisit that memory, i feel more alone than i ever have in my entire life. .
but things are a billion trillion times better now. that girl grew up and became someone i am proud to be â¤ï¸
.
i want to share that with you because get it. 
i went through my parentâ€™s terrible divorce. 
i was sexually abused by another child who was also being sexually abused. 
i had step sisters who had the opposite bodies as me and watched them get attention while i torturously compared myself to them every. single. day. 
i didnâ€™t know how to make friends. 
i felt alone. 
i cried myself to sleep. 
i didnâ€™t understand how to love myself. 
i never learned how to be bree.
.
i didnâ€™t even mean for this to be so raw, i guess itâ€™s been too long since the last time i spoke about it. .
if youâ€™re reading this, i see you. and i donâ€™t care where your pain is coming from. if youâ€™ve been through worse or if you donâ€™t even feel like youâ€™ve been through anything, it doesnâ€™t matter. if youâ€™re struggling, you donâ€™t have to justify your pain.
.
but you are stronger than the pain. sometimes you just need support so you can see that. reach out. reach out until youâ€™re heard. it took my mom, my boyfriend, and sharing my story in this community for me to finally be able to move forward. itâ€™s okay to need help. never be ashamed of needing helpâ¤ï¸

âœ¨soul up self loveâœ¨â£
â£
i applaud every single person who has ever found themselves in a dark place but rose above the pain and chose love instead. â£
â£
itâ€™s not easy choosing to do the hard work of loving yourself enough to dive deep into the black abyss of fear in order to conquer it one small thought and action at a time. â£
â£
we live in a world that has become accustomed to just putting a band aid â£
over anything uncomfortable. fear, pain, disease and even love. â£
â£
if needed, i challenge you to course correct starting now! â£
â£
trauma creates change we donâ€™t choose. â£
healing creates change we choose. â£
â£
choose to heal. â£
choose to love. â£
choose to live. â£
â£
choose to soul up! âœ¨ğŸ’ğŸ™ŒğŸ»â£
â£
tips to start your soul up journeyâ£
â£
1. have an open, beginners mindset. â£
2. meditate. creating stillness inside. â£
3. release suppressed emotions. â£
4. practice methodical, conscious breathing. â£
5. start to gain awareness of your thoughts, beliefs and judgments. â£
6. learn to trust your intuition. gut instinct is usually soul instinct. â£
7. do things you love everyday. â£
â£

text:
ritual abuse is a problem you don't see on the news very much 
going to read a few papers and see whether this is a topic covered in a credible database .. you don't get much research on this topic.

yet the problem is larger than people think because a bunch of children go missing every year. so where do you think they're all going? and why haven't these criminals been caught. 
maybe it's cos the whole ring circulates our government, judicial and regulatory bodies - i mean they've already found evidence of this in the past...look at britain.. so the issue is ongoing yet i don't see people concerned about it on the news. can't trust the powers that be and unfortunately they're the people who control what it is we all see on the news.. not everyone in government, judiciary and regulatory bodies are bad, but lots of them are psychopaths. you can argue that by doing five mins of research into psychopaths and then use your own logic to realise that these people are going to infiltrate positions of authority. and once they're in they get their cult friends in. pedogate is a mathematical probability, not a conspiracy.

#qanon #pedogate #pizzagate #metoo #violence

text:
yesterday we talked about developing a safety plan that outlines the ground rules and behaviors you will adopt as the primary caregivers for your children in order to keep them safe from sexual abuse. today, the question is how do you communicate with your family and other individuals who have access to your children what your safety plan entails and your expectations of them with regard to how they interact with your children?
1) be intentional. make a point to have an open and honest conversation with your family members, close family friends, and others. let them know you are concerned about your children's safety and you need their help and cooperation by adhering to a few "ground rules" that are designed to help prevent your children from being sexually abused.
2) point out problematic behaviors that you have noticed in the past without being accusatory. you may say something like "we really love to see how much fun the kids have playing with the family during family gatherings, we just ask that everyone refrain from playing the tickle game with them".
3) be willing to speak up when family members and others violate your safety plan. crossing boundaries is a key component in how predators groom children and their families. nip problematic behaviors in the bud immediately so your children don't become accustomed to having people touch them in inappropriate ways or being subjected to sexually explicit materials or conversation.
4) be willing to withdraw access to your children from anyone who is unwilling to adhere to your safety plan or consistently violates it.
what other ways can you think of that you can communicate with your family, friends, teachers, coaches, church leaders, physicians etc about your safety plan? #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl

text:
love? my world is full of it. love isn't always - and often isnâ€™t, for me - connected to sex or romance at all. eros, philia, agape... love surrounds us in all shapes and forms. i couldnâ€™t be be more grateful for the love i've found in the deep, compassion-filled friendships i've encountered over the past years. i made a terrifying leap in 2017 to live more vulnerably, authentically, out in the open, not knowing who would love me through it. coming out about my history as a trauma survivor was one of the scariest things i've ever done, but it freed me to openly walk this journey i'm on of learning to reclaim my body, my sense of touch and intimacy. and that side of love may take time, trust, and patience for me. but when i made that leap towards truth, i landed in the arms of a community that taught me the beauty of love without expectation or judgement. to be seen and honored for who you really are, and to be blessed with the opportunity to offer that same gift to others - that, to me, is the most beautiful love of all. happy agape day, today, tomorrow, and every other day. i love you all. ğŸ’•

and now for a john o'donohue quote:
"anam cara means soul friend. the anam cara was a person to whom you could reveal the hidden intimacies of your life. this friendship was an act of recognition and belonging. when you had an anam cara, your friendship cut across all convention and category. you were joined in an ancient and eternal way with the friend of your soul. in this love, you are understood without mask or pretension. the superficial and functional lies and half-truths of social acquaintance fall away, you can be as you really are. love allows understanding to dawn, and understanding is precious. where you are understood, you are at home. understanding nourishes belonging. when you really feel understood, you feel free to release yourself into the trust and shelter of the other person's soul." #love #friendship #agape #agapelove #survivor #metoo #healingjourney #demisexualpride #demiromanticpride #demisexual #demiromantic  #valentines

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this post is in response to a black female perspective.
â–
everything should be put in context. the accounts listed are facts. however, the conclusion on page 6 alludes to: extrapolation of the behavior of famous stars onto the general population is a recommendation.
â–
to imagine the average black man had behavior similar to those men mentioned in her story is not only opinion, it's a baseless opinion. whether it's yesteryear or today, black folk have a horrible tendency to live vicariously through celebrities being unable to approximate not only the financial wealth of their celebrity idol, but also the social status necessary to be immune to criticism and public scorn.
â–
at the time of the accounts listed, black families were still practicing mostly conservative christian social values. and at that time, those stars produced what was accused as secular "devil's" music. so it's unlikely, and even highly improbable the average black woman was being used as a "stepping stone" by the average black man.
â–
anyway, it's good to have the truth out in the open so we can process the corresponding emotion and sociopolitical implications.
â–
because the truth of the matter leads black folk to conclude: any struggle to assimilate into white society will be accompanied with deviant behavior because white society (mostly white capital) will pressure black men and women until deviant behavior is identified, and then white capital will reward those deviants with fame and fortune. which will allow the deviant behavior to continue with impunity; that is, until a #metoo strategy can be worked out in favor of white supremacy.
â–
so i believe the best recommendation after viewing these accounts, is to imagine what was the average black family life like. what was the average black family struggling with. (rather than to suppose that the average black female was being oppressed by the average black man.)
â–
a socio-political-economic revolution of the black collective consciousness is what is necessary here. we must evolve beyond so called american moral ideals. this is part of us developing our own culture and social justice. #blacknationalism #blackempowerment

text:
a break from my usual posts but i love this so i had to share!
â–
i am a champion for justice, but my reason for loving this today boils down to two words! marianne williamson. she is the spiritual teacher & activist behind the famous â€˜our deepest fear is not that we are inadequateâ€™ quote. (google it!).
â–
well known in the spiritual/human potential circles, i am excited that she is in the race because of who she is likely to influence. people like my friend liza!*
â–
marianne is the only person who could actually nudge liza out of her current â€˜rainbows and unicorns onlyâ€™ existence and get her to vote. ğŸ™ˆliza insists on living this way because she does not want to attract bad energy. to ensure this, she doesnâ€™t watch tv or read news & doesnâ€™t give a ratâ€™s bottom about politics.ğŸ¤¨ she does not vote! to me this equals giving up her civic right to be a part of policies that will affect the future of her children in exchange for a â€˜right-now-zen likeâ€™ existence.
â–
but why do i care? well, one, she is my friend. two, she is as sharp as a tack. previously a top notch lawyer about to make partner in a new york city firm, she quit her role when she realized she was pregnant with her first child, lucy. after child birth, she decided that she did not want to get back to the cut throat law environment. now she is a reiki healer and lives a totally mellow life.
â–
you probably know someone who like liza, has made a complete 180 degree career & lifestyle turnaround (the robin sharma effect aka the monk who sold his ferrari). a top notch surgeon one day and a tantric coach the next!
â–
it is my hope that liza will now be influenced by â€˜the marianne effectâ€™. i yearn for her to â€˜wake upâ€™ and take charge of whatâ€™s happening around her. even if it looks grim in the beginning, i know she can best handle it by being a part of the solution.
â–
and in the end, whether mw wins or not, at least the final tally will hopefully be more representative of everyoneâ€™s votes (including lizaâ€™s) & transcending all gender, faith and racial composition.
â–
do you have a friend like liza? thoughts about the current possibilities in the political front?

p.s. to liza, i love you! ğŸ’•
(* not her real name).

text:
.
putting this down in words was difficult.
and i hesitated before making it public.
.
but i felt that i had a duty to put this out here:
because there are few to no discussions about how victims recover from the trauma of sexual assault.
.
we expect it straightforward linear road to recovery,
and nobody talks about how that isnâ€™t the case at all.
.
about how every step forward is accompanied by 4-5 steps backwards.
about how little things â€” sights, smells, even words â€” can paralyse you, often without warning.
about how no period of time seems long enough, or distance far enough, for us to leave it all behind.
.
about how you will always feel as if a part of you was violently torn away from you,
wondering if you will ever find yourself whole again.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
know that there is help out there for anyone who has experienced sexual assault.

women's aid federation operate a 24/7 phone line, all details are below.

catherine ferrin from women's aid was kind enough to come into rehearsals last november to talk to our director and actors. she talked about the processes and help women's aid can provide for victims. she really helped us understand the themes we were undertaking.

there are still a few tickets available for our 2 performances in the american bar before we hit the road, taking wasted to school & community groups.

e-mail nuala@pintsizedni.com quoting either 3pm or 8pm and the no. of tickets you require.

we are kindly sponsored by the @departmentofjusticeni

#womensaidfederation #thisisnotconsent #metoo #endsexualassault #theatreineducation

text:
part. 3
"i need an anchor now, mama, to tell my stories.
but, mama with you i canâ€™t have such conversations.
you allowed him to destroy your heart.
your heart has turned into a heart of glass.
i fear it will break if i told you these stories.
mama, can you handle it if i told you
what prostitution did to me in this big city?
if i told you your sweet little girl grew up to be a bitter child;
a bitter teenager, and a bitter woman?
mama, can you handle it if i told you the actual reason

why i ended up in a mental institution?
after the man whom i had a business deal with betrayed me,
i was devastated, mama.
he bought himself a brand new car
with the loan i borrowed from the bank.
instead of purchasing the stock weâ€™d agreed on
he came back with a gorgeous yellow car from abroad.
i couldnâ€™t believe my ears when i got his response.
he called me a â€™slutâ€™. nobody had ever called me that.
for a moment, i was lost.
i didnâ€™t understand the purpose of this insult.
i was confused mama.
you know, â€˜money is the root of all evilâ€™;
i had never thought this saying was true until i experienced it." - lerato lehlabathe

you can now read her entire poem on our blog - http://wowement.blogg.se/

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: "we must understand that there is no consent between powerful and powerless. we get a lot of teacher - student cases where teachers exploit the students and say that there was consent of the student involved. in many developed countries, such things are criminalized between teacher and student or between employer and employee. when a person feels disempowered, or respectful, or fearful of the other person, they smile. this smile does not mean consent. compliance doesn't mean consent. not resisting does not mean consent. going to your teacher's office is not consent. we must redefine consent." â€” #arfanamallah in session: redefining  consent: power, pleasure, patriarchy â€” ğŸ“¸ @steermedia #lahootimelo #anodetowomen #metoo #ibelieveher #lahootimelo2019 #consent #lahooti #universityofsindh #qotd #futureisfemale

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

#taranaburke's career has been spent uniting us; #metoo allowed 19 million people across 85 countries to declare that we've been affected by sexual violence. @girlsforgenderequity, the non-profit she founded, creates opportunities for young women and girls to live self-determined lives by tackling the many obstacles young women and girls face such as sexism, racial inequality, homophobia, transphobia, and sexual harassment. her most recent work with the #muterkelly movement has allowed the rest of the world to connect to the scores of black women who have, until now, had to stand in silence as the violence, manipulation and abuse they suffered went ignored, and r kelly's wealth built. her involvement in the project has opened us to the prevalence of sexual violence, to its insidiousness, and to our ability to heal each other when we choose to #believewomen. 
for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

text:
aviation: holding you, i held everything (9/10) by nicholas jones, 19 january 2019. -

i canâ€™t think about what could have been when youâ€™re no longer here,
and as i try to put the words together - they begin to disappear,
because itâ€™s just too hard to accept the fact that i will never hear,
you sing along whenever your favorite song comes on,
ever again,

i canâ€™t think about the passenger side - windows rolled down,
and your hair being tossed in the wind,
or the way your smile could outshine,
the sun in the middle of a cool summer day,
by the pool,

itâ€™s only been a couple of weeks and i canâ€™t tell you what hurts more,
seeing you in my dreams and knowing this is all weâ€™ll ever be,
or living through each day looking for you in every person that i see,
wondering if i will ever be able to find my soul in someone else,
ever again,

regardless of how much time has passed,
i still think of you and me all of the time - especially at night,
when shooting stars cross paths to the rhythm of steel guitars,
because when i was holding you - i held everything,
i always needed. -

#
| posted: feb 14, 2019 12:01 am the opinions expressed by columnists are their own and do not represent the views of townhall.com. the powerful #metoo movement was established to address real injustices suffered by women -- and in some cases, although significantly less common, by men. this movement has undeniably affected societal norms and readjusted the fabric of american life.but such an important movement can be felled by its own excesses. in the wake of the #metoo movement, people are immediately rushing to judgment and to punishment of anyÂ accused individual -- in many cases, without due process. naturally, this moblike mentality to blindly punish an accused individual has the potential for far-reaching negative consequences -- namely, collateral damage to the falsely accused by those who misuse the movement for their own ambitious aims.take, for example, the domestic abuse allegations against johnny depp, which should serve as a cautionary tale. depp is a beloved actor who has won a 14 people's choice awards. he is, by all accounts, a serial monogamist. his first wife and three decades' worth of long-term girlfriends uniformly characterize him as a sensitive and caring partner.and then he met and married amber heard, who has madeâ€¦

- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
this week, my family dealt with an extremely stressful and traumatic issue that i can't discuss for legal reasons. 
yesterday we spent the whole day in a small room with 10 women and my beautiful, supportive, gentle and strong husband.
we experienced tears, laughter, long silences, meditation, shared food, frightened moments and more tears. 
there are many things that i'm trying to process from yesterday and will one day write about. however what is strong in my heart today is the power of the women (and one man) in that room, who ranged 5 decades and came together to carry each other through a highly emotive experience. 
i put on a strong face, when inside i was utterly terrified. but my family and friends gave me strength and i'll be forever grateful. 
i wish we didn't have to endure that experience, but we so lucky to have been surrounded by generous, loving souls. 
#womensupportingwomen #family #justice #truthcomesout #womenempowerment #metoo #timesup #chasingenso #rewriteyourstory #writewhatyoufeel #writer #myvillage #smallvictories

text:
the 2019 women's follows the 2017 women's march and 2018 women's march. in early 2017, during the aftermath of president trump's election, around four million people gathered in washington dc for the first women's march, a protest against legislation and rhetoric that harms women. however, news reports from across north america noted that turnout for the 2019 women's march was lower compared to previous years, with potential reasons being poor weather, a decline in interest and controversy over protest organization in the united states.
(photo by daniel rad)

text:
the 2019 women's follows the 2017 women's march and 2018 women's march. in early 2017, during the aftermath of president trump's election, around four million people gathered in washington dc for the first women's march, a protest against legislation and rhetoric that harms women. however, news reports from across north america noted that turnout for the 2019 women's march was lower compared to previous years, with potential reasons being poor weather, a decline in interest and controversy over protest organization in the united states.
(photo by daniel rad)

the students demand fair icc proceedings and safe college campus. that' not too much to ask, is it?

text:
perspective. one of the key concepts to keep in mind when mingling with others throughout your day. understanding that the lens you see through is what creates your reality. understanding that there is no select number of lens in the world, is important. everyone is different and different upbringings, history, experiences, relationships, environment and more all shape how we are and process things. be kind to your neighbors. be kind to those who may not get it. be kind to those who were raised differently than you. be kind to those who look different than you, speak differently than you, and think differently than you.
.

text:
my face washed away today when i received the call from my dad asking, â€œis the trial date still set to march 11, 2019?â€ me: yes as far as i know no one has called me and said anything differently. father: â€œwell i just heard that he was freed of all charges. me: my heart stop instantly. i immediately call the district attorneys only to get no response to find out that this matter was true. i did everything by the books of the law and they failed me tremendously. after being raped i went to emergency room and had s.a.n.e. kit done. re-living the story daily to get justice. i kept clothes that i had on the day i was raped. a no contact order was placed for my protection or at least i thought. until one day i saw my rapist, i did as i was instructed call the brandon police dept. if he didnâ€™t voluntarily remove himself. well he didnâ€™t. it took 11 accuracies for us to get a court date of this matter. to only be told the no contact paper that was signed meant if he was in my reach he would be arrested and held in jail until trial. well after 11 accuracies he didnâ€™t go to jail, i had witnesses of the matter and the judge whitney only gave him 24 months probation. i have been lied to by the rankin co. system since day one. iâ€™ve asked for anyone to help guide me for i saw things not making sense. so just when i left the decision/trust in the hands of the law they failed me. november 7, 2017 i was raped by corey armond beard. to find out today on february 13, 2019 through word of month he was freed blew my mind. did he pay someone to get him off, or did the system just fail me. i was told by daâ€™s office jessica you are strong one and i know you can/will get through this. however how do you know that i will, i was raped and with all evidence on the table you let him walk. i want justice, & need your help to know what to do when the law fails you...was my skin to dark was this a racial act that i wasnâ€™t protected? 
myo~voice .
.
.
.

text:
i live my life through a small window pane. i pretend no one can see me. no one knows my name. i cry when it rains to hide the tears. i pretend to enjoy life when others are near. who am i to think i deserve to be loved...to be wanted...to be needed...to be kissed...to be hugged? i used to see their faces when i closed my eyes. i used to hate living...i wanted to die. why didn't i find the courage to speak? why did those things keep happening to me? over and over even when i said no...the monsters kept coming...they wouldn't let go. maya angelou became a mute. i wish i did the same thing too. i live my life through a small window pane. i pretended no one could see me. no one knew my name. i still cry when it rains to hide my tears. i still pretend to enjoy life when others are near. guilt consumes my thoughts at times...but i'm so tired of the darkness, i accept the sunshine.
#metoo #survivor #speakup #yourvoicehaspower #youmatter #findthesunshine #endthesilence

text:
today i sat for almost 12 hours listening to testimony at the first #sexualharassment hearings in albany in 27 years.

there are so many way that victims of abuse and harassment cannot get justice for what happened to them, whether they report or not.

i came to honor their pain, show that we believe victims and because there have been moments where i have made others uncomfortable and i could not hold myself with integrity if i'm not taking responsibility and hearing from others on how to be better.

#albany #maleprivilege #metoo

text:
[cw: paedophilia, abuse] 
i have cried plenty of cathartic tears to your songs, @ryanadams, but tonight i am crying because you let me down.

when i was fourteen years old, my friend and his dad took me to your show in cardiff and it lit a fire inside me. until a few hours ago, you were one of my favourite artists. 
you, who inspired me to write and sing and play and be sad and loud and weird and proud, have proven yourself more of a disappointment than you could ever know.

for anyone reading this who hasn't had the misfortune of reading the new york times article yet, mister adams has been exposed for his three thousand explicit texts from his forty year old self to an underage girl, and a stream of women have come forward about his emotionally manipulative and abusive tendancies.

ryan, for my entire adult life, your songs have been my first choice for comfort when i have had to indulge in the beautiful pain of heartbreak. i honestly thought i would be a lifelong fan.

i hope you lose everything. with due respect to the other artists on pax-am, i hope that one day you learn of the forced sale of your label from a news reporter on a blurry screen in the dining hall of the grottiest prison new york has to offer.

i want you to know how deeply and bitterly you have disappointed someone who admired you.

in what was once my favourite song, you told me that you taught yourself how to grow old.

teach yourself how to grow the fuck up. ğŸ–•

#ryanadams #burnyourryanadamsrecords #paxam #metoo #dontsupportabusers

text:
the saddest thing i was told last year by a loved one was â€œme too.â€ sadness was not the only emotion i felt. a barrage of emotions flooded over me, and i wished i could have been there to protect them. though so many years have gone by, some of the hurt still remains not just from the abuse but from the ridicule they experienced when they went to other family members for help. the abuser no longer in the land of the living.  no justice, no peace? no, not so! this became their song in the night. â€œwhen peace, like a river, attendeth my way, 
when sorrows like sea billows roll; 
whatever my lot, thou hast taught me to say, 
it is well, it is well with my soul.â€

text:
some may say i am too much.
some may say i am not enough.
but i choose to love myself exactly as i am.

i am a soulful, rich, deep, embodied, heartfelt woman.
and i am not backing down.

i believe in myself and i want every woman in the world to believe in herself, too.

we had #metoo and we called it out.
now it's our time to do the inner work.
we are worthy. we are beautiful. 
we are powerful.
it's time to transform ourselves so we can transform this situation.

i will raise my voice. i will speak my truth. 
i will shine my light. i will be true to myself.
i declare i am finished giving my power away to anyone.
i am free! ğŸ’š

text:
healthy relationships feel good! 
this valentines day, we wish you all the love! 
february is a time to celebrate all the love, and it is also teen dating action month. there is a special hotline devoted to supporting teens called loveisrespect. you or your teen can reach out by calling 1-866-331-9474, texting loveis to 22522, or chatting online at loveisrespect.org.
want more valentine love? copy and paste this link into your browser. 
https://wscadv.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/valentine-cards.pdf and check hashtags #tdvam2019 #huddleup #tdvam to link to the national effort!

text:
about the book 
in the woman in the mirror, author evelyn mejil provides a vivid portrait of her courageous mind meeting her painful memories, her valiant heart overcoming her shameful unworthiness, and her bold spirit overpowering her relentless fear.
in this account, mejil shares an uncensored description of how she overcomes her past when she discovers an inconspicuous truth while traveling the world in search for answers to silence her nightmares and heal her pain. hidden in the eyes of the woman reflected in the mirror, she sees the answers stood where she buried her painful past, and to find them there is only one journey left to take, a journey within.
the woman in the mirror tells how once she goes beyond the memories and faces her demons, she finally discovers her true being and vividly recounts how her false self, the identity birthed in the lies of her past, collapses. shattering the iron grip of her past, she heals and brings forth a new story. mejil presents the unadulterated expression of her most powerful self, the authentic self.

tweet_full:
about the book 
in the woman in the mirror, author evelyn mejil provides a vivid portrait of her courageous mind meeting her painful memories, her valiant heart overcoming her shameful unworthiness, and her bold spirit overpowering her relentless fear.
in this account, mejil shares an uncensored description of how she overcomes her past when she discovers an inconspicuous truth while traveling the world in search for answers to silence her nightmares and heal her pain. hidden in the eyes of the woman reflected in the mirror, she sees the answers stood where she buried her painful past, and to find them there is only one journey left to take, a journey within.
the woman in the mirror tells how once she goes beyond the memories and faces her demons, she finally discovers her true being and vividly recounts how her false self, the identity birthed in the lies of her past, collapses. shattering the iron grip of her past, she heals and brings forth a new story. mejil presents the unadulterated expression of her most powerful self, the authentic self.

text:
on the occasion of valentine's day
page 01 premiere of theory fiction comic 
no thanks :) an androfeminist theory of love in the age of #metoo 
androfeminism views a man in sexual love as a toxic organism. as homo sapiens, we know that the term 'love' was an elizabethan overestimation of oxytocin superfluity that has gained traction in the last few centuries through sonnets, family dramas, presidential democracy, and rom coms, with romedy now as its ideological flagship. in the case study of peelipose chacko, we are considering the toxic sexual love. no one cares if jacques lacan said that there is nothing like sexual love. #instacomic #comics #graphicnovels #theoryfiction #feminist

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
"dare i disturb the universe?" the concept or luck or fortune as an arbitrary force that controls our lives is often personified as a woman. the roman godess fortuna was thought to dole out good or bad luck with the turn of her wheel. free will or choice is recognized as a means of circumventing luck, or using it to one's advantage. however, women themselves who make choices are often vilified. for eating from the tree of knowledge, the biblical eve is remembered as the corruptor of divine creation. today, women in many parts of the world are discouraged or prevented from making choices about their bodies, their educations, their marriages. Â here, i reinterpret the fruit as a symbol of humanity's first free act. a female figure evades fortuna and prepares to make a choice. in doing so, she may disturb the universe, but she understands that in a world so often governed by circumstance, choices are rare and precious things. .
.
.

text:
this year i want: renewal ğŸŒ¼
"the focus of my story is not on past traumaâ€”it is on everything that i am in spite of that: resilient, strong, courageous, brave, valuable, loved, and whole.  for too long iâ€™ve let myself be shrouded in shame, afraid of what the imperfections and the challenges i have faced in life say about me.  the reality is that i can be broken, but i cannot be destroyed. bravely confronting the dark and rejecting false responsibility is how i create space for my personal healing and growth. renewal is my battle cry.

this year, i am becoming what i already am but sometimes fail to see. i am extending myself the love that i give to others. renewal is the revitalization of myself and my life after the last year. it is a renewal of how i view and treat myself, a renewal of my faith, a renewal of my freedom, my power, and my courage. the villain in my story was not anyone or anything that brought me pain, it was my belief in the lie that anything or anyone could make me less than who i am.â€ -blackblessedblog (see the full story on our blog).

-trauma informed care-  in the u.s, one in three women experience some form of sexual violence in their lifetime, and the incidences are even higher for lgbtq individuals. for individuals who have experienced this type of trauma, going for a gyne exam or dealing with a pregnancy can be a potentially triggering experience. midwives have a unique opportunity to provide a safe, respectful space to provide necessary care without causing additional harm. this is called trauma-informed care, and itâ€™s something all clinicians should be providing to all individuals, regardless of a known history of trauma. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
some of the ways the omg midwives provide trauma informed care include:â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* screening for previous sexual trauma during visits and on our intake formsâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* starting the visit with our client fully clothedâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* determining first if a pelvic exam is even necessary or beneficial. we decide together if that is the right time for a pelvic exam â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* if our client consents to a pelvic exam, we offer a chaperone :an additional support person to be present during the examâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* before starting an exam, we receive consent again, and give our client the power to stop the exam at any pointâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* we offer and support speculum self insertion, and use the smallest possible speculum with lubricantâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* we can complete the exam without the use of stirrups. instead, our clientâ€™s legs are on the table, which is more comfortable and less exposed. they also have more control of their body and can reposition or move away as needed. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* we avoid using triggering language during our exams, and pay close attention to our clientâ€™s body language. if there is any feedback that portrays non-consent,  the exam is stopped.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
* this also applies in the context of pregnancy, with cervical exams: determining a need, receiving consent, ability to withdrawal consent at anytime, and making the exam as comfortable as possible. #traumainformedcare #survivor #lgbtq #healthycervix #thisiswhatmidwiferylookslike  #informedconsent  #metoo

text:
for nearly two decades, ryan adams, one of the most prolific singer-songwriters of his generation, has been heralded as a mercurial creative genius and a respected industry tastemaker.

he has also taken a special interest in the trajectory of female artists, especially younger ones, championing them onstage, across social media and in the studio, where his stamp of approval can jump-start careers.

some now say that adamsâ€™s rock-star patronage masked a darker reality. in interviews, seven women and more than a dozen associates described a pattern of manipulative behavior in which adams dangled career opportunities while simultaneously pursuing female artists for sex. in some cases, they said, he would turn domineering and vengeful, jerking away his offers of support when spurned, and subjecting women to emotional and verbal abuse, and harassment in texts and on social media. the accounts have been corroborated by family members or friends who were present at the time, as well as by correspondence from adams reviewed by the new york times.
_____

text:
join the #justice4gemmel coalition, #metoo international la and myself as we stand with male survivors of sexual harassment, sexual violence and exploitation! break the silence around male victims! arrest ed buck and demand justice for gemmel moore and timothy dean!

in light of recent allegations of sexual misconduct within gay men's chorus la (gmcla) involving artistic director jonathan weedman and west hollywood mayor john duran, we are announcing a press conference and peaceful rally to address a broader culture of complicity within west hollywood. 
for many of us who have respect for john duran's long legacy as a defender of lgbtq civil liberties, we are disheartened to see his contributions dampened by alleged behavior. 
meanwhile, the fight for justice for all victims of ed buck continues. the proximity of democratic leadership (including john duran) to prominent democratic donor- and alleged serial killer- ed buck is of concern to us all. 
we heal when we demand accountability from our own. city officials, commissioners and weho residents are invited to reaffirm our communities' solidarity with male survivors.

join us to make an intentional shift in tone in our community and say male survivors matter! align with justice for gemmel moore and timothy dean, and all survivors of ed buck!

our demands: 
1. arrest ed buck! end complicity by west hollywood city in the sexual predation of black queer men, sex workers, and people in survival economies in our community! john duran speak up about the crisis in your own west hollywood! 
2. demand accountability of gmcla creative director jonathan weedman and west hollywood mayor john duran! until results of a thorough, unbias investigation are complete, 
duran step down from city council! weedman step down from gmcla!

3. improved protocols throughout all city systems to build competency, and affirm the validity of male survivors of sexual harassment, sexual violence or exploitation. 
4. full transparency in city and gmcla finances in proximity to sexual misconduct allegations to rule out that revenues were not misused, endangering gmcla's organizational stability and the credibility of city of west hollywood

text:
a part of me..
you may never see.
you may never know.
you may never understand.
i am a representative for women and girls in economics , technology, sports, security, health care, education, politics, and above all development. 
i am part of the revolution. 
i am a bad feminist.
my place at the table is to protect all the rights of women and girls. 
and prove to the world; we are brighter, stronger, resilient, powerful and brave. 
we can reach the peak of our careers while keeping a home. 
we can be single mothers. 
we can be women with disabilities. 
we can be into entertainment and not prostitutes. 
we might have infertility issues due to health issues not abortion or uninformed assumptions. 
we can be bosses without using our bodies. 
we can be single on our own terms. 
we can be divorced not because we canâ€™t keep a home or we are too unruly. 
we might have mood swings but capable of leadership. 
we might be flashy but less demanding. 
we are capable of doing better than our past. 
our dress code is no indication of our personality. 
our #metoo stories are true and projects how rape culture threatens us daily. 
i am a woman that pledges to support, empower and mentor my kind. 
i am a woman 
you may never see. 
never know. 
never understand.

lisa flotlin, 29, was sexually assaulted by her high school spanish teacher when she was 17. eight years later, at 25, she realized she wanted to press charges but, due to convoluted statute of limitations laws, found out that she no longer had the option to seek justice. she is now sharing her story to help prompt changes to statute of limitations laws, including simplifying and extending the reporting period. photo by @gmartphoto.
#metoo #seattle #waleg #sexualassault

williams turned himself in to authorities.

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

learning how to say no, is one of the most life-changing gifts you can give yourself.  when we feel less-than, we have a tendency to do everything anyone asks of us, because we donâ€™t want anyone to be upset with us.  people donâ€™t respect you when you donâ€™t respect yourself.  i used to bend over backwards trying to do everything for everyone. i never wanted to upset anyone by saying noâ€”i couldnâ€™t help that time. what that did was make me even unhappier because i felt taken advantage of and i secretly and not-so-secretly resented it and then felt worse about myself for letting people blatantly take advantage of me.  itâ€™s a vicious cycle. helping others is a wonderful thing to do, but not when it becomes codependence. 
if you donâ€™t take care of yourself first, you canâ€™t help anyone else.  boundaries are a beautiful thing.
